{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 13:16:11.482644", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope summary\n- Goal: Verify end-to-end reachability for clients to DNS and web services, confirm OSPF propagation across the hierarchical core/distribution/server access layers, and ensure backend web network isolation per design.\n- Focus: Detect anomalies, localize any faulty devices, and identify root causes.\n\nKey findings from tests\n1) IP reachability\n- Hosts have expected addressing:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 = 10.1.1.10\n  - host_2_1_1_1 = 10.2.1.10\n- Server farm IPs present and reachable across the fabric (10.200.0.0/24).\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> load_balancer (10.200.0.7): ping OK (rtt ~1.7–4.1 ms).\n  - Multiple cross-host/server pings via get_reachability show 0% loss and low latency.\n- Backend network isolation validated:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> backend_web_0 (20.200.0.2): ICMP Destination Net Unreachable returned by 10.1.1.1 (dist-layer gateway), confirming 20.200.0.0/24 is not routable from user subnets (expected by design).\n\n2) DNS resolution\n- From host_1_1_1_1, hostnames resolve correctly via local DNS:\n  - web0.local -> 10.200.0.3\n  - web1.local -> 10.200.0.4\n  - web2.local -> 10.200.0.5\n  - web3.local -> 10.200.0.6\n  - web99.local -> 10.200.0.7\n\n3) HTTP application checks\n- From host_1_1_1_1, HTTP GET timing (curl) is consistently successful:\n  - web99.local (Nginx load balancer): total ~1.04–1.14 s across runs; TTFB ~0.24–0.34 s.\n  - Direct to web0.local–web3.local (Apache servers): similar totals (~1.01–1.18 s) and TTFB (~0.21–0.38 s).\n- No HTTP failures observed; responses are consistently delivered.\n\n4) Routing/OSPF state (FRR)\n- server_access_router routing table:\n  - 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected (br0).\n  - Host subnets 10.1.1.0/24 and 10.2.1.0/24 learned via OSPF over eth7 toward the core.\n- Core routers (router_core_1/2/3):\n  - Learn 10.200.0.0/24 via OSPF next-hops pointing to server_access_router side.\n  - Learn host subnets via OSPF as expected.\n  - No route for 20.200.0.0/24 on cores (not present in OSPF), which is correct for backend isolation.\n- Path metrics are coherent; no signs of flapping or inconsistencies in the displayed routes.\n\n5) Load balancer and backend segment configuration\n- load_balancer:\n  - eth0: 10.200.0.7/24 with default route via 10.200.0.1 (toward server access network).\n  - eth1: 20.200.0.1/24 (backend segment).\n- backend_web_0:\n  - eth0: 20.200.0.2/24 with default route via 20.200.0.1 (the load balancer).\n- Backend segment (20.200.0.0/24) shows as isolated L3 domain, only between LB and backend, not advertised into OSPF, matching design.\n\nAnomalies detected\n- None impacting reachability or service delivery were found.\n- Observed ICMP “Destination Net Unreachable” from user host to backend_web_0 (20.200.0.2) is expected due to intentional isolation of the backend network.\n\nObservations (non-blocking)\n- Slight variation in ICMP RTT from different web servers toward host_1_1_1_1 (some ~2.6–3.5 ms, others ~6 ms). Values remain low and stable; no packet loss noted.\n- HTTP TTFB and total times are broadly consistent between direct web servers and LB VIP, suggesting no obvious imbalance or backend path issues at this time.\n- The topology lists only backend_web_0 on the private 20.200.0.0/24 segment; although the description mentions three backends, the current lab appears to model a single backend. This is not causing any functional issues in the observed tests.\n\nConclusions\n- Overall network health: Normal.\n- OSPF domain is propagating necessary routes to host and server networks correctly; the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) is reachable end-to-end from user subnets.\n- DNS resolution is correct and consistent with service design.\n- HTTP services (web0–web3 and web99 LB) are reachable and responsive from hosts.\n- Backend network (20.200.0.0/24) is properly isolated and not reachable from host subnets, as intended.\n- No misrouted prefixes, blackholes, or service failures detected in the performed checks.\n\nFault localization and root cause\n- No active faults detected. The only unreachable target (20.200.0.2 from host) is by design due to backend isolation, not a failure.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 10098, "output_tokens": 4337, "total_tokens": 14435, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 7296}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3136}}}
